    <h2 id="tldr">TL;DR: Quick Recommendation</h2>
    <p>Short on time? Here is our 30-second summary based on product documentation, specification analysis, and feature evaluation of both platforms, covering startup and enterprise workflows. For deeper context, see our broader <a href="/best/">best-of rankings</a> and our <a href="/compare/">head-to-head comparisons</a>.</p>

    <div class="use-case">
      <h3>Who should choose Notion</h3>
      <p>Small to mid-size teams (1-100 people) who want an all-in-one workspace that combines docs, wikis, databases, and lightweight project management. Notion is ideal for product teams, startups, content teams, and anyone who values flexibility over rigid structure. Its flat-rate pricing on the Plus plan ($10/month for the whole workspace) makes it the most cost-effective choice for growing organizations. If you liked our <a href="/reviews/notion-vs-obsidian/">Notion vs Obsidian</a> breakdown, Notion is the more collaborative choice of those two.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="use-case">
      <h3>Who should choose Confluence</h3>
      <p>Enterprise organizations and engineering teams that already live in the Atlassian ecosystem. Confluence is the clear winner when you need deep Jira integration, granular page-level permissions, audit logs, approval workflows, and compliance certifications like SOC 2, FedRAMP, or ISO 27001. If your team uses Jira for issue tracking (see our <a href="/reviews/linear-vs-jira/">Linear vs Jira</a> comparison for context), Confluence is the natural documentation companion.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="use-case">
      <h3>Overall verdict</h3>
      <p>Both Notion and Confluence are excellent tools, but they excel at fundamentally different use cases. Notion wins on flexibility, pricing, and ease of use. Confluence wins on enterprise governance, developer workflows, and ecosystem depth. There is no universal winner; the right choice depends on team size, technical stack, and compliance requirements. Pairing them with complementary tools from our <a href="/best/">best productivity tools</a> list can extend their value further.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="use-case">
      <h3>Best alternative: ClickUp</h3>
      <p>If neither Notion nor Confluence feels quite right, our top alternative is ClickUp. It blends docs, tasks, and dashboards in a way that splits the difference between Notion's flexibility and Confluence's structure, with a free tier that supports unlimited users. We cover ClickUp and other strong alternatives in our dedicated <a href="/alternatives/">alternatives hub</a>, and we discuss it further in the alternatives section below.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="use-case">
      <h3>Bottom line</h3>
      <p>Choose Notion if your team is under ~100 people, values flexibility, and wants one tool for docs plus lightweight project management. Choose Confluence if you need enterprise-grade permissions, Jira integration, or compliance certifications. For everyone in between, test both free tiers for two weeks before committing. If you want to compare more documentation tools, browse our full <a href="/compare/">comparison library</a>.</p>
    </div>

