      <a href="https://www.notion.so" class="btn btn-primary" target="_blank">Try Notion Free →</a>
      <a href="https://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence" class="btn btn-secondary" target="_blank">Try Confluence Free →</a>
    </div>

    <h2 id="quick-comparison">Quick Comparison</h2>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Notion</th><th>Confluence</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Best For</td><td>All-in-one workspace, small teams</td><td>Enterprise documentation</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Free Tier</td><td>Generous, unlimited pages</td><td>3 users max (Free)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Pro Price</td><td>$10/mo (Plus)</td><td>$5.75/user/mo (Standard)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Templates</td><td>Rich template gallery</td><td>Extensive library</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Integration</td><td>Slack, Google Drive, Figma</td><td>Deep Jira integration</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Key Feature</td><td>Databases and linked pages</td><td>Enterprise permissions and workflows</td></tr>
        
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 id="what-is-notion">What Is Notion?</h2>
    <p>Notion was founded in 2013 by Ivan Zhao and Simon Last. It combines notes, documents, wikis, and project management into a flexible all-in-one workspace. Notion's block-based editor allows creating anything from simple meeting notes to complex databases with linked relationships. Its template gallery contains templates for everything from startup wikis to university coursework. Notion is particularly popular among startups, product teams, and small to mid-size organizations. The Plus plan costs $10 per month for unlimited users. Notion's appeal is its flexibility and ease of use for non-technical team members.</p>
    <h2 id="what-is-confluence">What Is Confluence?</h2>
    <p>Confluence was launched in 2004 by Atlassian and has become the standard documentation platform for enterprise organizations. It offers robust page hierarchies, templates, permissions, and approval workflows. Confluence integrates deeply with Jira, making it essential for development teams using the Atlassian ecosystem. It offers enterprise features like single sign-on, audit logs, data classification, and compliance certifications. Confluence Standard costs $5.75 per user per month. For large organizations with compliance requirements, Confluence's enterprise features are more comprehensive.</p>
    <h2 id="features">Features: Feature-by-Feature Comparison</h2>
    <h3>Documentation Flexibility</h3>
    <p>Notion's block editor and linked databases make it more flexible for creating interconnected documentation. You can embed databases, link to other pages, create dynamic views, and build interconnected knowledge bases without technical skills. Confluence offers a more traditional wiki experience with page trees and templates. For teams that want dynamic, interconnected documentation, Notion's flexibility is superior. For teams that prefer structured, hierarchical documentation, Confluence's approach is familiar and reliable.</p>

    <h3>Integration with Development</h3>
    <p>Confluence integrates deeply with Jira, allowing documentation to be linked to specific issues, epics, and releases. This creates a tight feedback loop between development work and documentation. Notion has good integrations with development tools but does not offer the same depth of Jira integration. For development teams using the Atlassian ecosystem, Confluence's Jira integration is essential for linking documentation to development workflows.</p>

    <h3>Enterprise Features and Permissions</h3>
    <p>Confluence offers granular permissions at space and page level, approval workflows for documentation review, audit logs for compliance, and data classification features. Notion's permission system is less granular, making it less suitable for organizations with strict access control requirements. For enterprises that need to control who can view, edit, and publish different types of content, Confluence's permission system is more comprehensive.</p>

    <h3>Pricing Model</h3>
    <p>Confluence Standard at $5.75 per user per month is cheaper per user for small teams but becomes expensive as teams grow. Notion Plus at $10 per month for unlimited users is significantly more affordable for growing teams. For a team of 50 people, Confluence costs $3,450 per year versus Notion's $120. Notion's pricing model clearly favors growing organizations, while Confluence's per-user pricing can become costly at scale.</p>
    <h2 id="performance">Performance</h2>
    <p>Notion provides a responsive web and desktop experience with page loads typically under 2 seconds. Databases with many linked entries can slow down. Search across workspace returns results in 1-2 seconds. Confluence on Atlassian Cloud performs reliably with page loads in 2-4 seconds. Search is comprehensive across spaces. Both platforms offer adequate performance, with Notion having a slight edge in speed for smaller workspaces. Confluence performs better at scale with hundreds of spaces and thousands of pages due to its more traditional database architecture.</p>
    <h2 id="pricing">Pricing</h2>
    <p>Notion Plus costs $10 per month for the entire workspace, regardless of user count. Business at $18 per user per month adds advanced features. Notion is free for individuals. Confluence Standard costs $5.75 per user per month. Premium at $11 per user adds AI features and analytics. For small teams of 1-5 people, Confluence is cheaper. For teams of 10+, Notion's flat-rate pricing becomes significantly more affordable. At 50 users, Notion Plus costs $10/month versus Confluence's $287/month.</p>

    <h2 id="ease-of-use">Ease of Use</h2>
    <p>Notion has the steeper edge in raw onboarding speed but the shallower learning curve for everyday use. New users can create a page, type, and publish in minutes thanks to the block-based editor that behaves like a familiar word processor. Templates and the slash command make common structures one keystroke away. Confluence's learning curve is steeper because users must understand spaces, page hierarchies, blueprints, and macros before they can be productive. Once learned, Confluence's conventions become second nature, but the initial ramp-up is a real cost for small teams.</p>
    <p>Mobile usability favors Notion by a wide margin. The Notion mobile app supports full editing with quick-capture buttons, while Confluence's mobile app is best treated as a read-only companion. For teams that draft or review content on the go, Notion is meaningfully easier to live with. Search discoverability also affects ease of use: Notion's natural-language Q&A lets non-technical users find answers without learning filter syntax, while Confluence's structured filters reward power users but intimidate casual contributors.</p>

    <h2 id="design">Design</h2>
    <p>Notion's interface is modern, minimal, and built around a single flexible canvas. The block-based editor uses consistent typography, generous whitespace, and subtle dividers, which makes content feel approachable even in long documents. Customization is light by design: there are no themes, no dark mode toggles beyond the system setting, and no extensive layout controls. The result is visual consistency across workspaces, at the cost of brand flexibility.</p>
    <p>Confluence's interface is more utilitarian and information-dense. The page header, breadcrumb trail, space sidebar, and macro toolbar all compete for attention, which can feel cluttered on smaller screens. Atlassian has modernized the look and feel over the past two years, but it still reads as enterprise software rather than a consumer product. Confluence offers stronger design control at the space level through headers, custom color schemes, and layout macros, which matters for organizations that want their internal docs to match brand guidelines.</p>
    <p>For teams that value a clean, modern aesthetic and minimal cognitive load, Notion is the better design choice. For teams that need pixel-level brand consistency across large documentation sets, Confluence offers more customization at the cost of visual polish.</p>

    <h2 id="real-world-testing">Real-World Workflow Analysis</h2>
    <p>Based on product documentation, specification analysis, feature evaluation, and workflow assessment, here is how Notion and Confluence compare across the workflows that matter most to teams evaluating these tools in 2026, including setup time, onboarding friction, search latency, mobile experience, and how each platform handles realistic workloads like onboarding docs, sprint retros, and incident postmortems.</p>

    <h3>Setup and configuration comparison</h3>
    <p>When configuring a Notion Business workspace and a Confluence Standard cloud instance in parallel, both can be connected to Slack for notifications, and the same content set can be mirrored into each: a company handbook, an engineering runbook, a product spec template, meeting notes, and a project tracker. The key differences emerge in how each platform handles permissions, search, and collaboration behavior under load.</p>

    <h3>Startup workflow: 5-person team</h3>
    <p>For a startup workflow, Notion is noticeably faster to set up. Within an hour, a workspace can have a homepage, three databases (tasks, projects, OKRs), and a meeting notes template. Confluence takes closer to half a day because spaces, space permissions, and page templates must be configured before writing a single doc. For a 5-person team where everyone wears multiple hats, Notion's "everything in one workspace" model wins on speed and simplicity. The ability to embed task boards directly next to product specs is something Confluence cannot do without Jira.</p>

    <h3>Enterprise workflow: 100+ person team</h3>
    <p>For an enterprise workflow, the result flips. With 100+ users split across engineering, product, design, sales, and legal, Confluence's space-level permissions and page restrictions keep content organized and access-controlled. Notion's sharing model, while improved, still requires careful workspace design to avoid accidental over-sharing. Confluence's audit log makes it trivial to answer "who viewed or edited this page," which is non-negotiable for compliance-heavy teams. For larger organizations, Confluence's governance model is the safer default.</p>

    <h3>Developer documentation workflow</h3>
    <p>For developer docs, Confluence retains its traditional edge. Code blocks with syntax highlighting, page templates for RFCs and architecture decision records, and the ability to embed Jira issue lists on a page make engineering workflows tighter. Notion's code blocks are decent, and its database views are great for tracking engineering tasks, but the lack of native Jira linking is a recurring friction point. If your engineering team lives in Jira, Confluence is the better doc home; if you use Linear (see our <a href="/reviews/linear-review/">Linear review</a>), Notion can fill the gap more comfortably.</p>

    <h3>Knowledge management workflow</h3>
    <p>For pure knowledge management, Notion's linked databases and backlinks make it easier to build an interconnected wiki where a single concept can surface in multiple views. Confluence's page tree is more rigid but more predictable: every page has exactly one home, which prevents the "where does this belong" question that plagues growing Notion workspaces. Based on feature analysis, Notion is better suited for product knowledge (specs, decisions, research) and Confluence for operational knowledge (runbooks, SOPs, policies).</p>

    <h3>Meeting notes workflow</h3>
    <p>Both tools handle meeting notes well, but in different ways. Notion's flexible blocks allow action items to be turned into linked database entries that auto-sync to task boards. Confluence's meeting notes blueprint generates a consistent, dated structure with attendees and action items, which is more standardized across a large team. For a small team that wants action items to flow into project tracking, Notion wins. For a large team that needs standardized, discoverable meeting records, Confluence wins.</p>

    <h3>Project management workflow</h3>
    <p>Notion can do real project management with board, timeline, and calendar views on top of databases. It is no replacement for a dedicated PM tool like those in our <a href="/reviews/monday-vs-asana/">Monday vs Asana</a> comparison, but for lightweight tracking it works. Confluence alone is not a project management tool; it relies on Jira for tasks and sprints. If you want project management built into your docs tool without buying a separate product, Notion is the clear choice.</p>

    <h3>Migration considerations</h3>
    <p>When migrating a Confluence space into Notion using HTML export and Notion's import, roughly 80% of content comes through cleanly, but macros (especially the Jira issue macro and status macro), page restrictions, and some table formats need manual cleanup. The reverse migration (Notion to Confluence) is harder because Notion's databases do not map to Confluence's page-based model. Budget 2-6 weeks for a real migration of any size, and treat it as an information architecture redesign, not a copy-paste job.</p>

    <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Pros and Cons</h2>

    <h3>Notion Pros</h3>
    <div class="pros-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Flexible block editor that adapts to almost any content type</li>
        <li>Powerful linked databases with multiple views (board, table, timeline, calendar, gallery)</li>
        <li>All-in-one workspace combining docs, wikis, tasks, and lightweight CRM</li>
        <li>Generous free tier for individuals and small teams</li>
        <li>Flat-rate Plus pricing ($10/month) is unbeatable value for growing teams</li>
        <li>Intuitive for non-technical team members with minimal onboarding</li>
        <li>Regular updates and a very active product roadmap</li>
        <li>Strong community template gallery and third-party integrations</li>
        <li>Notion AI for drafting, summarization, and workspace Q&A</li>
        <li>Excellent cross-platform sync across web, desktop, and mobile</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Notion Cons</h3>
    <div class="cons-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Limited enterprise governance compared to Confluence</li>
        <li>Less granular permissions; sharing is workspace-centric</li>
        <li>No native, deep Jira integration</li>
        <li>Can become disorganized at scale without a strict information architecture</li>
        <li>No built-in approval workflows for document review cycles</li>
        <li>Steeper learning curve for advanced databases and formulas</li>
        <li>Search can feel cluttered in workspaces with thousands of pages</li>
        <li>Offline support is limited; the app assumes connectivity</li>
        <li>Page load times degrade with very large, linked databases</li>
        <li>Compliance certifications trail Confluence for regulated industries</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Confluence Pros</h3>
    <div class="pros-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Enterprise-grade permissions at space and page level</li>
        <li>Deep, native Jira integration with bidirectional issue linking</li>
        <li>Built-in approval workflows for document review and publishing</li>
        <li>Page templates and blueprints for meeting notes, RFCs, and retros</li>
        <li>Compliance certifications including SOC 2, FedRAMP, and ISO 27001</li>
        <li>Audit logs and data classification for regulated industries</li>
        <li>Active development and frequent updates from Atlassian</li>
        <li>Growing community, marketplace apps, and ecosystem integrations</li>
        <li>Atlassian Intelligence for summarization and Jira issue generation</li>
        <li>Reliable performance at scale with thousands of pages across many spaces</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Confluence Cons</h3>
    <div class="cons-box">
      <ul>
        <li>Per-user pricing gets expensive fast as teams grow</li>
        <li>Steeper learning curve, especially for non-technical users</li>
        <li>Less flexible than Notion; rigid page-tree model</li>
        <li>Older interface design that can feel dated next to Notion</li>
        <li>Overkill for small teams that just need a wiki</li>
        <li>Interface can feel overwhelming with many spaces and macros</li>
        <li>Premium features like advanced analytics require higher-tier plans</li>
        <li>Free plan caps at 3 users, which excludes most real teams</li>
        <li>Migration to other tools is non-trivial because of macros and Jira links</li>
        <li>Mobile experience lags Notion for quick edits on the go</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2 id="who-should-choose">Who Should Choose Which?</h2>
    <p>Picking a winner between Notion and Confluence is less about which tool is "better" and more about which one fits your team's shape, stack, and constraints. Below we break down the ideal and not-ideal scenarios for each, based on product documentation, specification analysis, and feature evaluation of both platforms.</p>

    <h3>Perfect for Notion</h3>
    <div class="use-case">
      <p>Notion is the right call for startups and small to mid-size teams (roughly 1-100 people) that want one tool to handle docs, wikis, lightweight project management, and internal knowledge. It shines for product teams that need to link specs to tasks, content teams that want a single home for editorial calendars and style guides, and any team that values speed and flexibility over rigid structure. If your tech stack does not revolve around Jira, and you do not have heavy compliance requirements, Notion's flat-rate pricing and flexible editor make it the better default. For similar flexibility in a personal-knowledge context, see our <a href="/reviews/bear-notes-review/">Bear Notes review</a> and our <a href="/reviews/things-3-review/">Things 3 review</a>.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Perfect for Confluence</h3>
    <div class="use-case">
      <p>Confluence is the right call for engineering organizations and enterprises that already run on Atlassian. If your team uses Jira for issue tracking (see our <a href="/reviews/linear-vs-jira/">Linear vs Jira</a> comparison), needs page-level permissions for sensitive docs, requires audit logs and approval workflows for compliance, or operates in a regulated industry like finance, healthcare, or government, Confluence is the safer, more complete choice. It is also a strong fit for any team that has outgrown Notion's governance and needs predictable structure across hundreds of spaces.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Not ideal for Notion</h3>
    <div class="use-case">
      <p>Notion is not ideal for large enterprises (500+ users) with strict compliance needs, regulated industries that require FedRAMP or SOC 2 Type II certifications, engineering teams whose entire workflow is built around Jira, and organizations that need formal approval workflows for document publishing. It is also a poor fit if your team needs deep offline support or granular page-level access control. In those cases, Confluence or a dedicated tool like GitBook for developer docs will serve you better.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Not ideal for Confluence</h3>
    <div class="use-case">
      <p>Confluence is not ideal for small teams (under 10 people) that just need a flexible wiki, content teams that want to combine docs with project tracking in one place, startups that want to minimize per-seat costs, and any team that values a modern, block-based editor over a traditional wiki. It is also overkill if you do not use Jira; without Jira, much of Confluence's value is locked away. For lightweight alternatives, browse our <a href="/alternatives/">alternatives hub</a> or check our <a href="/reviews/trello-review/">Trello review</a> for simpler collaboration.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 id="use-cases">Real-World Use Cases</h2>

      <div class="use-case">
    <h3>Development Teams</h3>
    <p>Confluence's deep Jira integration makes it the clear choice for engineering documentation. Developers can embed live Jira issue lists on architecture pages, link pull requests to decisions, and use blueprints for RFCs and postmortems. If your engineering org uses Jira (compare alternatives in our <a href="/reviews/linear-vs-jira/">Linear vs Jira</a> breakdown), Confluence is the natural documentation home.</p>
