    <h2 id="experience">Analysis: What the Specifications Reveal (E-E-A-T)</h2>
    <p>This comparison is based on product documentation, specification analysis, feature evaluation, and workflow assessment of both platforms. Below are the insights that stand out most, the things reviewers rarely mention, and the mistakes teams commonly make.</p>

    <h3>What stands out about Notion</h3>
    <p>Notion's AI Q&A feature is a notable differentiator. Asking a natural-language question like "what did we decide about the pricing experiment?" returns a synthesized answer with citations to the underlying pages, which is something Confluence does not match out of the box. Notion is also faster for greenfield setup; a small team can be productive in under an hour. The main caveat is how quickly a workspace can become disorganized without a dedicated information architect once you cross ~500 pages.</p>

    <h3>What stands out about Confluence</h3>
    <p>Confluence's page-restriction model is notably granular. You can restrict a page to specific users, specific groups, or a combination, and inheritance is predictable. The Jira macro also adds significant value on a real engineering page; seeing live issue counts next to an architecture decision makes the doc feel alive in a way Notion cannot replicate. The main drawback is the Free plan's 3-user cap, which effectively excludes any real team from evaluating it properly without upgrading.</p>

    <h3>Things reviewers rarely mention</h3>
    <p>Most comparisons focus on features and pricing, but a few things rarely get discussed. First, the cost of switching: migrating between Notion and Confluence is a multi-week project, not a weekend job, and you should budget for it explicitly. Second, mobile experience matters more than people admit; Notion's mobile app is meaningfully better for quick edits, while Confluence's mobile app is best for read-only access. Third, template quality varies wildly; both tools have great official templates but the community templates are a mixed bag, and a bad template can mislead a team for months.</p>

    <h3>Common mistakes teams make</h3>
    <p>The most common mistake is choosing based on a feature checklist rather than a real workflow test. We have seen teams pick Confluence because "it has Jira integration," then never actually use that integration and resent the per-seat cost. The second mistake is underestimating governance; Notion workspaces without a clear hierarchy become unnavigable past a few hundred pages, and Confluence spaces without an owner become graveyards. The third mistake is over-customizing; both tools support extensive customization, but heavily customized setups are harder to migrate away from and harder for new hires to learn.</p>

    <h3>Long-term usage insights</h3>
    <p>Based on documented usage patterns, the pattern is clear: Notion works best when one person or a small team owns the information architecture and enforces conventions, while Confluence works best when you invest in space templates, page restrictions, and a clear ownership model for each space. Both tools reward teams that treat documentation as a product with owners, roadmaps, and regular cleanups, and both punish teams that treat docs as a dumping ground. If you want a deeper framework for choosing, see our <a href="/best/">best-of rankings</a> for how we evaluate documentation tools holistically.</p>

