    <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide: How to Choose Between Notion and Confluence</h2>
    <p>Choosing between Notion and Confluence is a multi-year commitment, so it pays to think through the decision carefully. This buying guide walks through what to consider, common mistakes to avoid, budget recommendations by team size, and the often-overlooked cost of long-term lock-in.</p>

    <h3>What to consider before choosing</h3>
    <p>Start with your team size, your existing tech stack, and your compliance requirements. If you are under 100 people, not on Jira, and not in a regulated industry, Notion is almost always the better default. If you are over 100 people, on Jira, or in a regulated industry, Confluence is the safer choice. Next, consider your team's technical sophistication: non-technical teams adapt to Notion faster, while engineering teams often prefer Confluence's structure. Finally, think about your documentation philosophy: do you want a flexible graph of linked content (Notion) or a predictable tree of spaces and pages (Confluence)?</p>

    <h3>Common mistakes to avoid</h3>
    <p>The biggest mistake is choosing based on a single feature without testing the full workflow. The second is ignoring migration cost; moving between these tools later is expensive, so it is worth getting the decision right the first time. The third is overbuying; many teams pay for Confluence Premium or Notion Business when Standard or Plus would suffice. The fourth is underestimating governance; both tools need an owner and clear conventions, or they devolve into a mess.</p>

    <h3>Budget recommendation by team size</h3>
