    <h3>Long-term ownership cost and migration lock-in</h3>
    <p>The sticker price is only part of the cost. Both Notion and Confluence create lock-in through content, integrations, and team habits. Migrating a 1,000-page workspace between them typically costs 2-6 weeks of dedicated effort plus content cleanup, and some features (Notion databases, Confluence macros) do not transfer cleanly. Factor in the cost of potential migration when you choose, especially if your team is growing fast and might outgrow the smaller-scale tool. For teams that anticipate significant growth, Confluence's scalability at the high end can outweigh Notion's pricing advantage at the low end.</p>

    <h2>Special Comparison: Startup vs Enterprise vs Developer Workflows</h2>
    <p>To make this comparison more concrete, here is how Notion and Confluence stack up across three of the most common workflows we see in 2026, plus a deep dive on AI capabilities, pricing by team size, migration difficulty, and the underlying knowledge-management philosophy.</p>

    <h3>Startup use case comparison</h3>
    <p>For a 5-person startup, Notion is the clear winner. Setup takes under an hour, the Plus plan costs $10/month flat, and the team gets docs, wikis, a lightweight CRM, and project tracking in one workspace. Confluence takes longer to set up, costs $28.75/month for the same team on Standard, and feels like overkill without Jira. The only reason a startup should pick Confluence is if they are already deeply invested in the Atlassian ecosystem or expect to scale past 100 people within a year.</p>

    <h3>Enterprise use case comparison</h3>
    <p>For a 500-person enterprise, Confluence is the clear winner. Its space-level permissions, audit logs, approval workflows, and compliance certifications give IT and security teams the controls they need. Notion's Enterprise plan has closed the gap on SSO and audit logs, but its permission model is still less granular and its compliance certification portfolio is thinner. Enterprises in regulated industries (finance, healthcare, government) should default to Confluence unless they have a specific reason to consider Notion.</p>

    <h3>Developer documentation workflow</h3>
    <p>For developer docs, Confluence retains its edge thanks to native Jira linking, code blocks with syntax highlighting, and blueprints for RFCs and architecture decision records. Notion's code blocks are decent, and its database views work well for tracking engineering work, but the lack of native Jira linking is a real friction point. If your engineering team uses Linear instead of Jira (see our <a href="/reviews/linear-review/">Linear review</a>), Notion closes much of the gap because both tools have a modern, API-first feel. For publishing public developer docs, GitBook is also worth a look.</p>

    <h3>AI capability comparison: Notion AI vs Confluence Intelligence</h3>
    <p>Both platforms have invested heavily in AI. Notion AI excels at drafting content, summarizing pages, autofilling database properties, and answering natural-language questions across your workspace. It feels more polished for writers and content teams. Confluence Intelligence (powered by Atlassian Intelligence) focuses on summarizing pages, generating Jira issues from text, and answering questions across the Atlassian suite, which makes it stronger for engineering and ops context. Based on feature documentation, Notion AI is oriented toward better drafts while Confluence Intelligence is oriented toward better cross-product answers. For a wider look at AI writing tools, see our <a href="/reviews/notion-ai-vs-grammarly/">Notion AI vs Grammarly</a> and <a href="/reviews/jasper-vs-copyai/">Jasper vs Copy.ai</a> comparisons.</p>

    <h3>Pricing comparison by team size</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <tr><th>Team size</th><th>Notion Plus (flat)</th><th>Confluence Standard (per user)</th><th>Savings with Notion</th></tr>
        <tr><td>5 users</td><td>$10/mo</td><td>$28.75/mo</td><td>$18.75/mo</td></tr>
        <tr><td>25 users</td><td>$10/mo</td><td>$143.75/mo</td><td>$133.75/mo</td></tr>
        <tr><td>100 users</td><td>$10/mo</td><td>$575/mo</td><td>$565/mo</td></tr>
        <tr><td>500 users</td><td>$10/mo*</td><td>$2,875/mo</td><td>$2,865/mo</td></tr>
