    <p>*Notion Plus is flat-rate, but teams of 500 typically need Notion Business ($18/user/mo) or Enterprise for advanced permissions, which changes the math. At 500 users on Notion Business, cost is $9,000/month versus Confluence Standard at $2,875/month, so Confluence becomes cheaper per seat at very large scale. Always model both options at your actual team size before deciding.</p>

    <h3>Migration difficulty analysis</h3>
    <p>Migrating from Confluence to Notion is moderately difficult. Notion supports HTML and Markdown import, which handles most text content, but Confluence macros (especially the Jira issue macro), page restrictions, and some table formats need manual cleanup. Expect 80% of content to transfer cleanly and 20% to need rebuilding. Migrating from Notion to Confluence is harder because Notion's databases do not map to Confluence's page-tree model; you typically have to flatten databases into individual pages or rebuild them as Confluence tables. Budget 2-6 weeks for any migration of meaningful size, and treat it as an information-architecture redesign.</p>

    <h3>Knowledge management philosophy difference</h3>
    <p>The deepest difference between Notion and Confluence is philosophical. Notion treats knowledge as a graph: pages link to pages, databases reference databases, and a single concept can surface in multiple views. This is powerful for interconnected, evolving knowledge like product specs and research. Confluence treats knowledge as a tree: every page has exactly one parent in exactly one space, which makes ownership and discovery predictable but limits cross-referencing. Neither approach is universally better; the right choice depends on whether your team thinks in graphs or trees.</p>

    <h3>Real workflow walkthroughs</h3>
    <p>To make this concrete, here are two representative workflows. Workflow 1: a product manager drafting a PRD. In Notion, she can create a page, embed a roadmap database, link related specs, and use AI to summarize customer feedback, all in one workspace in about 30 minutes. In Confluence, she can create a page from the PRD blueprint, embed a Jira epic list, and link related pages, which takes about 45 minutes but produces a more standardized output. Workflow 2: an engineering team writing a postmortem. In Confluence, the postmortem blueprint auto-populates sections (summary, timeline, root cause, action items) and links action items to Jira issues. In Notion, the team can build a similar template from scratch and use a database to track action items, which is more flexible but less standardized.</p>

    <h3>Decision tree: if X, then choose Y</h3>
    <p>If your team is under 50 people and not on Jira, choose Notion. If your team is over 100 people or in a regulated industry, choose Confluence. If you are on Jira and want docs tightly linked to engineering work, choose Confluence. If you want one tool for docs and lightweight project management, choose Notion. If you need granular page-level permissions or audit logs, choose Confluence. If you want the best AI writing experience, choose Notion. If you want the best AI cross-product Q&A in the Atlassian suite, choose Confluence. If you are a solo user or researcher, consider Obsidian (see our <a href="/reviews/obsidian-review/">Obsidian review</a>) or our <a href="/reviews/notion-vs-obsidian/">Notion vs Obsidian</a> comparison. If you want docs plus PM in one tool and neither Notion nor Confluence fits, consider ClickUp.</p>

    <h2 id="verdict">Final Verdict</h2>

    <div class="verdict">
      <h2>Our Verdict</h2>
      <p>Based on product documentation, specification analysis, feature evaluation, and workflow assessment across startup and enterprise use cases, Notion and Confluence are both excellent documentation tools that excel at fundamentally different use cases. There is no universal winner, and any review that declares one objectively better than the other is oversimplifying a decision that genuinely depends on your team's size, stack, and constraints.</p>
      <p><strong>Choose Notion if</strong> you are a small to mid-size team (roughly 1-100 people) that values flexibility, wants one workspace for docs and lightweight project management, and does not need deep Jira integration or enterprise compliance certifications. Notion's flat-rate Plus pricing at $10/month for the entire workspace makes it the most cost-effective choice for growing teams, and its block-based editor plus linked databases give you a flexibility that Confluence cannot match. The trade-off is that Notion's permission model is less granular, its compliance certifications are thinner, and very large workspaces can become disorganized without a dedicated information architect.</p>
      <p><strong>Choose Confluence if</strong> you are an enterprise or engineering organization that needs granular page-level permissions, audit logs, approval workflows, compliance certifications (SOC 2, FedRAMP, ISO 27001), or deep Jira integration. Confluence's per-user pricing gets expensive at scale, but its governance model, Atlassian ecosystem integration, and reliability at hundreds of spaces and thousands of pages are unmatched. The trade-off is that Confluence feels heavier and less modern than Notion, and small teams will find it overkill.</p>
      <p><strong>For teams in between</strong>, the decision comes down to your tech stack and growth trajectory. If you are on Jira and expect to grow past 100 people within a year, start with Confluence to avoid a painful migration later. If you are not on Jira and value speed and flexibility, start with Notion and revisit if you outgrow it. Both tools offer free tiers, so the lowest-risk path is to run a two-week pilot of each with your actual team and actual content before committing.</p>
      <p><strong>Best alternative:</strong> if neither feels right, ClickUp is our top pick for teams that want docs and project management in one tool, and Obsidian is our top pick for individuals who want powerful local-first knowledge management. Browse our <a href="/alternatives/">alternatives hub</a> for more options.</p>
      <p><strong>Bottom line:</strong> Notion wins on flexibility, pricing, and ease of use. Confluence wins on enterprise governance, developer workflows, and ecosystem depth. Both are excellent choices in the productivity and documentation category, and your final decision should be based on your specific requirements, budget, and preferred workflow. We recommend testing both platforms with their free tiers before committing to a paid plan, and revisiting the decision annually as both products continue to evolve rapidly.</p>
    </div>

