    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <p>Here are the most common questions from teams choosing between Notion and Confluence. These answers are based on product documentation, specification analysis, and feature evaluation of both tools. For more comparisons, browse our <a href="/compare/">comparison library</a> or our <a href="/best/">best-of rankings</a>.</p>

    <h3>Is Notion better than Confluence?</h3>
    <p>It depends on your specific use case and priorities. Notion offers more flexibility and better value for documentation, especially for small to mid-size teams. Confluence is the enterprise standard with unmatched Jira integration and stronger compliance features. Consider your primary workflow needs, team size, and tech stack when choosing between them. If you want a deeper framework, our <a href="/best/">best-of rankings</a> walk through how we evaluate documentation tools.</p>

    <h3>Which is more affordable?</h3>
    <p>Notion is significantly more affordable for growing teams because its Plus plan is a flat $10 per month for the entire workspace, while Confluence charges $5.75 per user per month. At 50 users, Notion Plus costs $10/month versus Confluence's $287/month. For small teams of 1-3 people, Confluence Free can be cheaper, but Notion scales better as headcount grows. Always confirm current pricing on the official <a href="https://www.notion.so/pricing" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Notion</a> and <a href="https://www.atlassian.com/software/confluence/pricing" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Atlassian</a> pricing pages.</p>

    <h3>Can Notion replace Confluence?</h3>
    <p>Notion can replace Confluence for small to mid-size teams that do not rely on deep Jira integration or enterprise compliance features. However, organizations that require granular page-level permissions, audit logs, approval workflows, and tight Atlassian ecosystem integration will still need Confluence. Many teams run both in parallel, using Notion for product docs and Confluence for engineering knowledge bases.</p>

    <h3>Is Confluence good for small teams?</h3>
    <p>Confluence can work for small teams, especially those already using Jira or Trello, but it is often overkill. The Free plan limits you to 3 users, and the per-user pricing adds up quickly. Small teams typically find Notion's flat-rate pricing and flexible editor better suited to their needs unless they specifically need Confluence's structured page hierarchies and approval workflows. For simpler collaboration, our <a href="/reviews/trello-review/">Trello review</a> may also be relevant.</p>

    <h3>Does Notion integrate with Jira?</h3>
    <p>Notion does not have native, deep Jira integration like Confluence does. You can connect Notion to Jira through third-party tools like Zapier, Make, or the unofficial embed approach, but you will not get the bidirectional linking of issues, epics, and releases that Confluence offers out of the box. If Jira integration is a core workflow requirement, Confluence is the better choice. See our <a href="/reviews/linear-vs-jira/">Linear vs Jira</a> comparison for more on Jira-centric workflows.</p>

    <h3>Which is better for developers?</h3>
    <p>Confluence is generally better for developer documentation because of its native Jira integration, page templates for RFCs and architecture decisions, code blocks with syntax highlighting, and approval workflows for technical specs. Notion is better for cross-functional developer teams that want to combine docs, project tracking, and product specs in one workspace. If your engineering team uses Linear instead of Jira, see our <a href="/reviews/linear-review/">Linear review</a> for a compatible stack.</p>

    <h3>Can I migrate from Confluence to Notion?</h3>
    <p>Yes, but migration requires planning. Notion supports importing Confluence spaces via HTML or Markdown export, but page hierarchies, macros, and some Confluence-specific features do not transfer cleanly. Most teams rebuild their information architecture in Notion rather than doing a direct port. For large Confluence spaces, expect a 2-6 week migration effort with content cleanup. The reverse migration (Notion to Confluence) is harder because Notion's databases do not map to Confluence's page-based model.</p>

    <h3>Which has better AI features?</h3>
    <p>Both platforms have invested in AI. Notion AI offers writing assistance, summarization, Q&A across your workspace, and autofill for database properties, making it well-suited for content-heavy workflows. Confluence Intelligence (powered by Atlassian Intelligence) focuses on summarizing pages, generating Jira issues from text, and answering questions across Atlassian products. Notion AI is more polished for writers; Confluence AI is stronger for engineering and ops context. For more on AI writing tools, see our <a href="/reviews/notion-ai-vs-grammarly/">Notion AI vs Grammarly</a> and <a href="/reviews/jasper-vs-copyai/">Jasper vs Copy.ai</a> comparisons.</p>

